		<div class="listing-header">
										<h1>Related developments</h1>
				
						<br class="cl"/>
		</div> 
		<div id="listing-items">
			
							
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Results-and-innovations-from-transnational-research-partnerships" title="Results and innovations from transnational research partnerships" alt="link">Results and innovations from transnational research partnerships</a></h2>

	
					<p>The objective of this research fair organised in June 2013 by the Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation (SDC) and the Swiss Commission for Research Partnerships with Developing &nbsp;Countries (KFPE) was to enable exchange and dialogue between science, policy, and practice for securing global public goods in the context of sustainable development. From this page, &nbsp;you can download presentations by key staff of participating organisations on topics such as ‘Getting research and innovation into policy and practice’.In his presentation, François Münger, Head of the Global Programme on Water Initiatives at SDC, details the barriers to linking research, policy and practice, such as: Low recognition and &nbsp;rating of practice and policy influence in a academic cursus; Difference of timing between research and political rhythms which limits the possibility to take advantage of the political &nbsp;opportunities; Results often presented to potential users at the end of research project. According to him, transdisciplinary and multi-stakeholder approaches can further innovation by &nbsp;connecting researchers to larger networks or introduce them to transdisciplinary approaches that can help them think out of the box. Research partnership is an important strategic option to &nbsp;connect policy and research.(KFPE, 06/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Results-and-innovations-from-transnational-research-partnerships">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Farmer-s-choice-of-seeds-in-four-EU-countries-under-different-levels-of-GM-crop-adoption" title="Farmer’s choice of seeds in four EU countries under different levels of GM crop adoption" alt="link">Farmer’s choice of seeds in four EU countries under different levels of GM crop adoption</a></h2>

	
					<p>Researcher Angelika Hilbeck at the Institute of Integrative Biology of the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology looked into the agricultural seed catalogues available to farmers in countries &nbsp;with different degrees of GM crop adoption (Austria, Germany, Spain, and Switzerland). She and her colleagues estimated how much real-world choice in seeds maize farmers have in each &nbsp;of the countries. The results show that, between 1995 and 2011, in the countries that did not adopt GM crop (Austria, Germany and Switzerland), actual restrictions and regulations of GM &nbsp;crops have not decreased seed choices/cultivar availability for farmers. In contrast, they observed that in Spain, which has adopted GM maize, the seed market was more concentrated with &nbsp;fewer differentiated cultivars on offer: the overall number of maize cultivars declined. The research also plotted the yields over the time period only to note that there was no reduction in yields &nbsp;in non-adopting countries.(Environmental Sciences Europe 2013, 25:12 doi:10.1186/2190-4715-25-12)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Farmer-s-choice-of-seeds-in-four-EU-countries-under-different-levels-of-GM-crop-adoption">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/The-global-hidden-hunger-indices-and-maps-an-advocacy-tool-for-action" title="The global hidden hunger indices and maps: an advocacy tool for action" alt="link">The global hidden hunger indices and maps: an advocacy tool for action</a></h2>

	
					<p>Indices and maps of global hidden hunger are being developed to help prioritise programme assistance and to serve as an evidence-based global advocacy tool. In this research paper, &nbsp;Sumithra Muthayya of Sax Institute Sydney, Australia together with specialists from both the non-profit and for-profit nutrition sectors, creates two types of hidden hunger indices and maps &nbsp;(using data on stunting, anaemia, retinol levels and estimates of Disability Adjusted Life Years (DALYs) attributed to micronutrient deficiencies). Of note, occurrence of iodine deficiency did &nbsp;not conform to that of other micronutrients (it mainly occurs in developed countries). The study demonstrates how these indices and maps provide crucial data for tackling global multiple &nbsp;micronutrient deficiencies and could help to scale up effective nutrition interventions.(<i>PLoS ONE</i> 8(6): e67860. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0067860. June 2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/The-global-hidden-hunger-indices-and-maps-an-advocacy-tool-for-action">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Plant-biotechnology-Tarnished-promise" title="Plant biotechnology: Tarnished promise " alt="link">Plant biotechnology: Tarnished promise </a></h2>

	
					<p>A&nbsp;<i>Nature</i>&nbsp;special issue on GM crops explores the evidence behind some of the most controversial claims about the technology, the impact of the negative attitudes towards this research field, recent advancements such as membrane transporters, and the engineering behind the second generation of GM crops. In this special issue, editors argue that GM research needs to happen outside of the industry (in the non-profit sector) so that developments are driven by objectives other than profit. Key messages point to the profit-driven GM crop development for industrial agriculture that may benefit only national revenues at the expense of smallholders and better livehoods for rural populations. GM crops for the poor to help them combat malnutrition, secure higher yields and save on expensive input is one among several other viable options that can improve the agri-food systems in developing countries. &nbsp;(<a href="http://www.nature.com/news/plant-biotechnology-tarnished-promise-1.12894?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_blank"><i>Nature</i></a>, adapted from&nbsp;<a href="http://clippings.ilri.org/2013/05/02/nature-takes-a-hard-look-at-the-messy-middle-ground-the-difficult-adolescence-of-gm-crops/?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_blank">ILRI</a>, 02/05/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Plant-biotechnology-Tarnished-promise">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Best-practices-for-organic-agriculture-policy-in-developing-countries" title="Best practices for organic agriculture policy in developing countries" alt="link">Best practices for organic agriculture policy in developing countries</a></h2>

	
					<p>This UNCTA-UNEP/CBTF study recommends that developing country governments should play a facilitating role and engage with stakeholders when developing their organic policies. It presents an evaluation of several country case studies (South Africa). It notes that compliance with international standards is necessary if countries are to realise the benefits from organic agriculture and that they should build the requisite capacities through education, research, extension and other aspects. Recommendations are made for general policy, standards and regulations, markets, production and other including, training, education and research. The need for specialised research and development programmes and prioritisation of organic research avenues is acknowledged. &nbsp;(<a href="http://www.unep.ch/etb/publications/UNCTAD_DITC_TED_2007_3.pdf?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_self">UNEP-UNCTAD</a>, 2008)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Best-practices-for-organic-agriculture-policy-in-developing-countries">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Does-rapid-agricultural-growth-require-a-system-of-innovation-Evidence-from-Ghana-and-Burkina-Faso" title="Does rapid agricultural growth require a system of innovation? Evidence from Ghana and Burkina Faso " alt="link">Does rapid agricultural growth require a system of innovation? Evidence from Ghana and Burkina Faso </a></h2>

	
					<p>The ‘systems of innovation’ hypothesis is tested to determine if a dynamic and growth oriented agricultural sector is not possible without a functional system of innovation (SI). The researchers moved away from the national system of innovation to highlight the ways that the SI manifests itself using a selection of crops in Ghana and Burkina Faso (plantain, maize, millet, yam, sorghum) that have shown significant growth in production over the last two decades.&nbsp;Using two indicators (a common understanding on objectives and priorities, and a high level of interactivity), the authors find (i) little evidence of common understanding of the objectives or priorities of the SI and (ii) low levels of interactivity. They noted that where there is interaction, it is mainly passive/informal. They concluded that there is weak evidence of the existence of anything that might be considered a high functioning SI. Increases in yield could have been attributed to increased acreage more than to increases in productivity and not to the SI. They are of the view that the most satisfactory explanation linking growth and a functioning SI may only become evident when farmers have exhausted the possibilities of easy wins. From a policy perspective, they suggest that it may be more opportunistic to target investment in agricultural research and other activities that support innovation.&nbsp;(via&nbsp;<a href="http://www.future-agricultures.org/research/science-technology-and-innovation/7847-working-paper-does-rapid-agricultural-growth-require-a-system-of-innovation-evidence-from-ghana-a-burkina-faso?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_self">Future Agricultures Consortium</a>, 01/05/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/Does-rapid-agricultural-growth-require-a-system-of-innovation-Evidence-from-Ghana-and-Burkina-Faso">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/LCIRAH-policy-briefs-on-under-nutrition-released" title="LCIRAH policy briefs on under-nutrition released" alt="link">LCIRAH policy briefs on under-nutrition released</a></h2>

	
					<p>The Leverhulme Centre for Integrative Research on Agriculture and Health (LCIRAH) was established to build a new inter-sectoral and interdisciplinary platform for integrating research in agriculture and health, with a focus on international development goals. The aim is to better address complex global issues surrounding the need to feed nine billion people healthily by 2050. Its research focuses on how to improve nutrition outcomes through agricultural interventions, such as the introduction of nutritious crop varieties, educational programmes or government policies that make healthy foods more affordable. The June 2013 policy briefs reveal that: 1. Existing agricultural research methods fail to measure nutritional outcomes; 2. Agricultural interventions place different demands on women’s resources and time: how they can have a positive nutritional effect without additional burdens. &nbsp;(<a href="http://www.lcirah.ac.uk/node/122?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_blank">LCIRAH</a>, 06/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/LCIRAH-policy-briefs-on-under-nutrition-released">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/The-challenge-of-measuring-performance-of-agricultural-conservation-and-environmental-programmes" title="The challenge of measuring performance of agricultural conservation and environmental programmes" alt="link">The challenge of measuring performance of agricultural conservation and environmental programmes</a></h2>

	
					<p>This report commissioned by AGree summarises conceptual and methodological challenges of measuring the environmental performance of agriculture. The authors acknowledge that there is no comprehensive, widely accepted index or assessment tool which considers all the related factors concerning the impact of agricultural operations, practices and systems on defined environmental goals for water, wetlands restoration, and native species among others.&nbsp;Different types of performance measures and approaches are reviewed to identify best practices and enhance understanding of the ways in which agricultural and environmental policy might be assessed and strengthened. One main recommendation is that it may be beneficial to engage farmers and ranchers early in the collection and interpretation of data. While it is emphasised that agricultural and environmental policies have distinct purposes, the authors conclude that neither should be pursued in isolation. They conclude that aligning agricultural production with improved environmental outcomes at the landscape scale is a long-term goal achieved through collaboration among various agencies and levels of government, producers, researchers, private companies and civil society. &nbsp;
&nbsp;(<a href="http://www.foodandagpolicy.org/sites/default/files/AGree%20Ag%20Conserv%20and%20Environ-Apr%202013.pdf?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_blank">AGree</a>, 01/04/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/The-challenge-of-measuring-performance-of-agricultural-conservation-and-environmental-programmes">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/How-can-universities-influence-development-policy" title="How can universities influence development policy? " alt="link">How can universities influence development policy? </a></h2>

	
					<p>Members of the Evidence-Based Policy in Development Network (EBPDN) debated what universities could do to get their academic research ‘out there’. Some interesting suggestions included: ‘collective action as no single or isolated sector in society can accomplish the desired changes’, ‘updating the universities’ methods and contents so students grasp the fast-changing world of knowledge’, ‘creating policy research institutes to focus research on priority areas’ and ‘conducting research that respond to issues that are policy relevant’. Three specific strategies were suggested: (1) working with public officials to enhance and/or find ways to improve the implementation mechanism; (2) engaging in policy debates that address priority issues; and (3) having student conduct local needs assessment and share results with policymakers and local communities.<a href="http://www.drussa.net/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=1931" target="_self">http://www.drussa.net/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=1931</a> (Drussa, 28/05/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/How-can-universities-influence-development-policy">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/What-counts-as-good-evidence" title="What counts as good evidence? " alt="link">What counts as good evidence? </a></h2>

	
					<p>This briefing paper argues that there is ‘no simple answer to the question of what counts as good evidence’ if public services are to deliver more for less. The authors focus on evidence that is underpinned by research as opposed to expert opinion or stakeholder views. &nbsp;In debating the issue of evidence quality, they consider research as a ‘way of knowing’ while acknowledging that there are other ways: empirical, theoretical and experiential. Their overall argument is that the evidence quality depends on the ‘what’, ‘why’ and ‘for whom’ dimensions as they differentiate between the needs of policymakers and decision-makers. While consensus is possible among sub-groups of stakeholders on what is considered as good evidence, overall consensus is potentially an unreachable goal as power relations can also shape the outcomes. The issues addressed here, for example on the hierarchies of evidence and quality, standards and matrices of evidence, are interesting and relevant for all stakeholders involved in shaping complex and politicised decision-making. &nbsp;(<a href="http://www.nesta.org.uk/library/documents/A4UEprovocationpaper2.pdf?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_May2013" target="_self">Research Unit for Research Utilisation (RURU), University of St Andrews</a>, 11/2012)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/ACP-agricultural-S-T-dialogue/Related-developments/What-counts-as-good-evidence">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
